:::summary
Immanuel Kant (1724–1804) was the German philosopher whose *Critique of Pure Reason* (1781) fundamentally reoriented Western philosophy by distinguishing what the human mind can know from what transcends its reach — and whose moral philosophy, centered on the categorical imperative, provided the most rigorous account of duty and human dignity in the modern philosophical tradition, acknowledging that morality points toward God even if it cannot be grounded in empirical knowledge of him.
:::

